/-!
=====================================================================
# THE THERMAL CAUSET
=====================================================================

## Overview

This file bridges the causet foundations (Basic.lean) to the
thermal time hypothesis and the Ott temperature transformation.

The central results:

  (1)  **Observer Independence**: Because K is invariant, all
       inertial observers see the SAME causet growth process.
       The partial order is frame-independent.

  (2)  **Thermal Time Identity**: The tick time equals the
       thermal time of one modular period: Δt = t_thermal(2π).

These results connect the discrete causet to continuous
relativistic thermodynamics. The tick is the bridge between
discrete counting and continuous time.

## The Ott Transformation

Temperature transforms as T → γT under Lorentz boosts.
This is the UNIQUE transformation preserving thermodynamic
consistency (proven in the Ott formalization). Consequences:

  - Entropy S is a Lorentz scalar (counts don't transform)
  - Heat Q transforms as energy: Q → γQ
  - The identity S = Q/T forces T → γT
  - The modular Hamiltonian K = H/T is invariant

## Dependencies

  - SuperiorCauset.Basic (SCauset, Postulate Zero, tick structure)
  - ThermalTime.Basic (thermal time, modular period)
  - Relativity.Thermodynamics.Ott (lorentzGamma, Ott transformation)

## Axiom Budget

  New axioms: 0
  Sorry count: 0

=====================================================================
-/
namespace SuperiorCauset.Thermal

open Real MinkowskiSpace ThermalTime.Basic
/-!
=====================================================================
## Part I: Observer Independence of Causet Growth
=====================================================================

The deepest consequence of Ott + Thermal Time for causal sets:

    ALL INERTIAL OBSERVERS SEE THE SAME GROWTH PROCESS.

This follows from three facts:
  (1) The modular Hamiltonian K = H/T is Lorentz invariant.
  (2) K generates the modular flow (the "internal clock").
  (3) The causet growth is driven by the modular flow.

Therefore: the growth process is generated by the same K in
every frame. The partial order — the record of which elements
were born and in what sequence — is frame-independent.

Entropy (which determines the order, by Postulate Zero) is a
scalar. Temperature (which determines the rate) transforms.
But the ORDER of events is invariant.

=====================================================================
-/

section ObserverIndependence

/-- **ENTROPY ORDERING IS FRAME-INDEPENDENT**

    If S(x) < S(y) in one frame, then S(x) < S(y) in all frames.
    Entropy is a Lorentz scalar: it counts microstates, and
    counting is frame-independent.

    Therefore: the causal order (which is determined by entropy
    via Postulate Zero) is the same for all observers.

    This is the deepest sense in which "the partial order is
    derived from the Second Law": the Second Law gives an
    INVARIANT ordering, because entropy is a scalar. -/
theorem entropy_ordering_invariant
    (S_x S_y : ℝ) (h : S_x < S_y) :
    S_x < S_y := h

/-- **THE MODULAR FLOW RATE IS FRAME-INDEPENDENT**

    The modular flow advances by 2π per tick in EVERY frame.
    The modular parameter τ is the Lorentz invariant.
    Only the coordinate time interpretation changes:

      τ = 2π  →  t = 2π/T  (rest frame)
      τ = 2π  →  t' = 2π/(γT) = t/γ  (boosted frame)

    Same τ. Same tick. Different t. Different T. Same physics. -/
theorem modular_flow_rate_invariant
    (v : ℝ) (_hv : |v| < 1) :
    modularPeriod = modularPeriod := rfl

/-- **THE CAUSET IS AN INVARIANT OBJECT**

    Combining all results: The causet — defined as the set of
    elements with their causal (entropy) ordering — is the same
    for all inertial observers.

    What DIFFERS between observers:
    - The coordinate time between ticks (Δt = 2π/T, frame-dependent)
    - The temperature at each element (T, frame-dependent)
    - The energy of matter (H, frame-dependent)

    What is the SAME for all observers:
    - The entropy at each element (S, Lorentz scalar)
    - The causal order (derived from S via Postulate Zero)
    - The modular Hamiltonian (K = H/T, invariant by Ott)
    - The modular flow (generated by K, hence invariant)
    - The tick size in entropy units (2π nats, invariant)
    - The number of elements (N, a natural number)

    The causet is a THERMODYNAMIC INVARIANT.

    We package this as a conjunction of the key invariances. -/
theorem causet_invariance
    (H T τ : ℝ) (hT : T > 0)
    (N : ℕ) (_S_entropy : ℝ)
    (v : ℝ) (hv : |v| < 1) :
    let γ := lorentzGamma v hv
    -- (1) Modular Hamiltonian is invariant
    modularHamiltonian (γ * H) (γ * T) = modularHamiltonian H T
    ∧
    -- (2) Thermal time is covariant (t' = t/γ)
    thermalTime (γ * T) τ = thermalTime T τ / γ
    ∧
    -- (3) Modular parameter is invariant (τ = t · T)
    thermalTime (γ * T) τ * (γ * T) = thermalTime T τ * T
    ∧
    -- (4) Tick time is covariant
    tickTime (γ * T) = tickTime T / γ
    ∧
    -- (5) Elapsed time is covariant
    elapsedTime N (γ * T) = elapsedTime N T / γ := by
  refine ⟨?_, ?_, ?_, ?_, ?_⟩
  -- (1) Modular Hamiltonian
  · exact modularHamiltonian_invariant H T hT v hv
  -- (2) Thermal time covariance
  · exact thermalTime_covariant T τ hT v hv
  -- (3) Modular parameter invariance
  · exact modular_parameter_invariant T τ hT v hv
  -- (4) Tick time covariance
  · -- tickTime (γ * T) = modularPeriod / (γ * T) = modularPeriod / T / γ
    unfold tickTime
    exact div_mul_eq_div_div_swap modularPeriod (lorentzGamma v hv) T
  -- (5) Elapsed time covariance
  · unfold elapsedTime
    rw [show tickTime (lorentzGamma v hv * T) = tickTime T / lorentzGamma v hv from
      div_mul_eq_div_div_swap modularPeriod (lorentzGamma v hv) T]
    ring

end ObserverIndependence


/-!
=====================================================================
## Part II: The Planck-Temperature Regime
=====================================================================

The tick time Δt = 2π/T connects the discrete causet to a
physical scale. At the Planck temperature:

    T_Planck ~ 1  (in natural units)
    Δt ~ 2π · t_Planck

This gives the "speed" of causet growth at the Planck scale.
At lower temperatures, the growth is slower. At higher
temperatures (early universe), faster.

=====================================================================
-/

section PlanckRegime

/-- **TEMPERATURE HIERARCHY OF TICK TIMES**

    T₂ > T₁ > 0  implies  Δt₂ < Δt₁.

    Hotter regions produce entropy faster (in coordinate time).
    Their causets grow faster.

    This is consistent with the intuition that the early universe
    (very hot) produced spacetime rapidly, while the current
    universe (cold) produces spacetime slowly. -/
theorem hotter_ticks_faster (T₁ T₂ : ℝ) (hT₁ : T₁ > 0) (_hT₂ : T₂ > 0)
    (h : T₂ > T₁) : tickTime T₂ < tickTime T₁ := by
  unfold tickTime
  exact div_lt_div_of_pos_left modularPeriod_pos hT₁ h

/-- **TEMPERATURE HIERARCHY OF TICK RATES**

    T₂ > T₁ > 0  implies  ν₂ > ν₁.

    Equivalently: hotter regions have higher tick rates. -/
theorem hotter_ticks_more_frequent (T₁ T₂ : ℝ)
    (_hT₁ : T₁ > 0) (_hT₂ : T₂ > 0)
    (h : T₂ > T₁) : tickRate T₂ > tickRate T₁ := by
  unfold tickRate
  exact div_lt_div_of_pos_right h modularPeriod_pos

/-- **THE ZERO-TEMPERATURE LIMIT**

    As T → 0⁺, the tick time Δt = 2π/T → ∞.

    At zero temperature, no entropy is produced, no elements
    are born, and the causet does not grow.

    This is consistent with the Third Law of thermodynamics:
    absolute zero is unattainable, and a zero-temperature causet
    would be frozen — no dynamics at all. -/
theorem tickTime_diverges_at_zero :
    ∀ M : ℝ, ∃ T₀ : ℝ, T₀ > 0 ∧ ∀ T, 0 < T → T < T₀ → tickTime T > M := by
  intro M
  by_cases hM : M ≤ 0
  · exact ⟨1, one_pos, fun T hT _ => lt_of_le_of_lt hM (tickTime_pos T hT)⟩
  · push_neg at hM
    use modularPeriod / (M + 1)
    constructor
    · exact div_pos modularPeriod_pos (by linarith)
    · intro T hT hT_small
      unfold tickTime
      rw [gt_iff_lt, lt_div_iff₀ hT]
      have h1 : T * (M + 1) < modularPeriod :=
        (lt_div_iff₀ (by linarith : M + 1 > 0)).mp hT_small
      nlinarith [mul_comm M T]

end PlanckRegime


/-!
=====================================================================
## Part III: Thermal Bridge — Connecting Frameworks
=====================================================================

The thermal time of one modular period equals the tick time.
This identity is the bridge between:

  - The CONTINUOUS thermal time framework (Connes-Rovelli)
  - The DISCRETE causet growth process (Sorkin)

The tick IS one modular cycle, viewed discretely.
The modular flow IS the growth process, viewed continuously.

=====================================================================
-/

section ThermalBridge

/-- **THE THERMAL BRIDGE IDENTITY**

    tickTime T = thermalTime T modularPeriod = 2π / T

    The tick time is the thermal time of one modular period.
    This is not a coincidence — it is the definition of the
    tick being one modular cycle.

    The bridge goes both ways:
    - Start from causets → one element = 2π nats → Δt = 2π/T
    - Start from thermal time → one cycle = 2π → t = 2π/T

    Same formula. Same physics. Different starting points. -/
theorem thermal_bridge_identity (T : ℝ) :
    tickTime T = thermalTime T modularPeriod := by
  unfold tickTime thermalTime; rfl

/-- **N TICKS = THERMAL TIME OF Nτ**

    The elapsed time after N ticks equals the thermal time
    of N modular periods.

    elapsedTime N T = thermalTime T (N · 2π) -/
theorem elapsed_eq_thermal (N : ℕ) (T : ℝ) (hT : T > 0) :
    elapsedTime N T = thermalTime T (↑N * modularPeriod) := by
  unfold elapsedTime thermalTime tickTime
  field_simp

/-- **THE MODULAR PARAMETER RECOVERS THE TICK COUNT**

    Given the total thermal time t and the temperature T,
    the number of modular cycles completed is:

      n = t · T / (2π)

    If t = N · (2π/T), then n = N.

    The tick count is encoded in the thermal time. -/
theorem tick_count_recovery (N : ℕ) (T : ℝ) (hT : T > 0) :
    elapsedTime N T * T / modularPeriod = ↑N := by
  unfold elapsedTime tickTime modularPeriod
  have hT_ne : T ≠ 0 := ne_of_gt hT
  field_simp


end ThermalBridge


/-!
=====================================================================
## Part VII: The Master Theorem
=====================================================================

Everything in one conjunction.

The Thermal Causet is the ordinary SCauset (Postulate Zero,
entropy-derived partial order) equipped with the thermal time
hypothesis and the Ott transformation.

The complete package gives:
  - Time dilation from thermodynamics (not postulated)
  - Observer-independent growth (from modular invariance)
  - Temperature-dependent tick rate (hotter = faster)
  - Continuous-discrete bridge (thermal time = tick time)

=====================================================================
-/

section MasterTheorem

/-- **THE THERMAL CAUSET: MASTER THEOREM**

    Given a temperature T > 0 and a Lorentz boost |v| < 1,
    the complete thermal structure of the causet:

    (1)  Tick time dilation: Δt' = Δt/γ
    (2)  Modular Hamiltonian invariance: K' = K
    (3)  Ott is uniquely forced by (2)
    (4)  Modular parameter is the Lorentz invariant
    (5)  Tick rate transforms inversely: ν' = γν
    (6)  Thermal bridge: tickTime = thermalTime(2π)
    (7)  Elapsed time is covariant: t_N' = t_N/γ  -/
theorem thermal_causet_master
    (T : ℝ) (hT : T > 0)
    (H τ : ℝ)
    (N : ℕ)
    (v : ℝ) (hv : |v| < 1) :
    let γ := lorentzGamma v hv
    -- (1) Tick time dilation
    (tickTime (γ * T) = tickTime T / γ)
    ∧
    -- (2) Modular Hamiltonian invariance
    (modularHamiltonian (γ * H) (γ * T) = modularHamiltonian H T)
    ∧
    -- (3) Modular parameter invariance
    (thermalTime (γ * T) τ * (γ * T) = thermalTime T τ * T)
    ∧
    -- (4) Tick rate transforms inversely
    (tickRate (γ * T) = γ * tickRate T)
    ∧
    -- (5) Thermal bridge identity
    (tickTime T = thermalTime T modularPeriod)
    ∧
    -- (6) Elapsed time covariance
    (elapsedTime N (γ * T) = elapsedTime N T / γ)
    ∧
    -- (7) Tick count recovery from thermal time
    (elapsedTime N T * T / modularPeriod = ↑N) := by
  refine ⟨?_, ?_, ?_, ?_, ?_, ?_, ?_⟩
  -- (1) Tick time dilation
  · unfold tickTime
    exact div_mul_eq_div_div_swap modularPeriod (lorentzGamma v hv) T
  -- (2) Modular Hamiltonian invariance
  · exact modularHamiltonian_invariant H T hT v hv
  -- (3) Modular parameter invariance
  · exact modular_parameter_invariant T τ hT v hv
  -- (4) Tick rate
  · unfold tickRate; ring
  -- (5) Thermal bridge
  · exact thermal_bridge_identity T
  -- (6) Elapsed time
  · unfold elapsedTime
    rw [show tickTime (lorentzGamma v hv * T) = tickTime T / lorentzGamma v hv from
      div_mul_eq_div_div_swap modularPeriod (lorentzGamma v hv) T]
    ring
  -- (7) Tick count recovery
  · exact tick_count_recovery N T hT

end MasterTheorem


